"title": "COE",
"body": "‚óè‚Äã COE = comprehensive oral examination\n      ‚óè‚Äã a COE is completed on all new patients at UIC COD that have not been seen before\n              ‚óã‚Äã screening appointment ‚Üí patient is accepted ‚Üí patient goes to radiology for radiographs ‚Üí COE appointments\n      ‚óè‚Äã the patient must have a pano & FMX completed before the COE\n              ‚óã‚Äã pt can bring copies of recent FMX/pan from outside dentist, but they must be of good enough quality to be\n                   diagnostic\n      ‚óè‚Äã a COE consists of 3 parts:\n              1.‚Äã perio COE\n              2.‚Äã restorative COE\n              3.‚Äã treatment plan presentation\n      ‚óè‚Äã usually the perio COE is done before the restorative COE, so that the restorative instructors are able to take the perio\n         diagnosis into consideration\n              ‚óã‚Äã this isn‚Äôt a rule though ‚Äî it‚Äôs ok to do the restorative COE first if you have to (ex: if perio chairs are all booked up\n                   and you have an open restorative chair)\n      ‚óè‚Äã the perio COE must be completed in a perio chair\n      ‚óè‚Äã the restorative COE should be completed in a restorative chair, however can be completed in a perio chair after the perio\n         COE if restorative faculty is available (usually OK, before you start the restorative COE, just ask a restorative instructor who is\n         free if they have time to help you)\n      ‚óè‚Äã the instructor you do the restorative COE with will be the instructor you do the treatment plan presentation with, and also\n         the instructor you will do all phase 3 work with\n      ‚óè‚Äã take diagnostic impressions at the perio COE ‚Äî this way, if they don‚Äôt turn out or you need to retake, you have the\n         restorative COE appointment to retake before you need diagnostic casts at the tx planning appointment"
