"body": "peds appointment color\n    ‚óè‚Äã white = operative\n    ‚óè‚Äã green = initial exam (COE)\n    ‚óè‚Äã purple = recall exam (POE)\n\nstages of the dentition\n    ‚óè‚Äã primary dentition: all primary teeth ‚Äî 6 months - 6 years\n    ‚óè‚Äã early mixed dentition: eruption of permanent first molars + incisors ‚Äî 6 - 9 years\n    ‚óè‚Äã intermediate period: 1-2 year waiting period during which no teeth erupt ‚Äî 9 - 10 years\n    ‚óè‚Äã late mixed dentition: eruption of permanent canines + premolars + 2nd molars ‚Äî 10 - 13 years\n    ‚óè‚Äã permanent dentition: loss of all primary teeth ‚Äî 12 - 13 years +\n\nincisor liability\n     ‚óè‚Äã incisor liability: the discrepancy between the amount of space required by & the amount of space available for the\n          permanent incisors (primary incisors are much smaller mesiodistally than the permanent incisors)\n     ‚óè‚Äã incisor liability is overcome by 3 means: (a) anterior eruption & proclination of permanent incisors;\n          (b) increase in intercanine width; (c) anterior spacing in the primary dentition\n\nspaces & shifts\n    ‚óè‚Äã primate space: a space mesial to maxillary primary canines & distal to mandibular primary canines\n    ‚óè‚Äã the early mesial shift results in loss of primate space due to eruption of the permanent first molars\n    ‚óè‚Äã leeway space: the difference in mesiodistal width between: the primary canine + primary molars & the\n        permanent canine + permanent premolars\n             ‚óã‚Äã maxillary leeway space is 1.5 mm per side, 3 mm per arch\n             ‚óã‚Äã mandibular leeway space is 2.5 mm per side, 5 mm per arch\n    ‚óè‚Äã the late mesial shift results in loss of leeway space due to mesial shift of erupting permanent premolars\n\nocclusion in the primary dentition\n    ‚óè‚Äã before permanent molar eruption, Angle classification cannot be determined, however it can be predicted based on the\n        position of the primary second molars\n              (1)‚Äã flush terminal plane\n                        ‚óè‚Äã with minimal growth ‚Üí end-to-end permanent molars\n                        ‚óè‚Äã with forward growth of mandible ‚Üí class I permanent molars\n              (2)‚Äã mesial step\n                        ‚óè‚Äã with minimal growth ‚Üí class I permanent molars\n                        ‚óè‚Äã with forward growth of mandible ‚Üí class III permanent molars\n              (3)‚Äã distal step\n                        ‚óè‚Äã with minimal growth ‚Üí class II permanent molars\n                        ‚óè‚Äã with forward growth of mandible ‚Üí end-to-end molars permanent molars\n\nFrankl behavior rating scale\n               Definitely negative. Refusal of treatment, forceful crying, fearfulness, or any other overt evidence of extreme negativism.\n 1     ‚Äì‚Äì\n               Patients that you are not able to treat due to behavior. Likely will require advanced techniques to treat.\n\n               Negative. Reluctance to accept treatment, uncooperative, some evidence of negative attitude but not pronounced\n 2      ‚Äì\n               (sullen, withdrawn). The work can be completed but is a struggle. May require advanced techniques.\n\n               Positive. Acceptance of treatment; cautious behavior at times; willingness to comply with the dentist, at times with\n 3      +      reservation, but patient follows the dentist‚Äôs directions cooperatively. Work is finished, patient is generally happy but may\n               have struggled a bit. Can be managed with basic techniques. Be sure to document difficult areas for future visits.\n\n               Definitely positive. Good rapport with the dentist, interest in the dental procedures, laughter and enjoyment. Little effort\n 4     ++\n               needed for behavior management.\n\npediatric anesthetic\n    ‚óè‚Äã maximum dose for pediatric patients is 4.4 mg per kg of body weight\n    ‚óè‚Äã always use the regular (20 mm, 30g) blue needle in peds patients, even for IAN\n             ‚óã‚Äã only exception is large teens (age 12+) for IAN; check with instructor first\n\nAAPD max dose\n                    maximum number of 1.8 mL carpules\n                                                        2% Lidocaine\n     pt age        pt weight (lb)    pt weight (kg)\n                                                      number of carpules\n      1 yr             16.5               7.5                 0.9\n                       22.0              10.0                 1.2\n     2-3 yr\n                       27.5              12.5                 1.5\n                       33.0              15.0                 1.8\n     4-5 yr\n                       38.5              17.5                 2.1\n                       44.0              20.0                 2.4\n     6-8 yr\n                       49.5              22.5                 2.8\n                       55.0              25.0                 3.1\n     9-10 yr\n                       66.0              30.0                 3.7\n                       71.5              32.5                 4.0\n                       77.0              35.0                 4.3\n     11+ yr\n                       82.5              37.5                 4.6\n                       88.0              40.0                 4.9\n\n      carpules of            minimum\n     2% lidocaine          pt weight (lb)\n              1                     18\n             1.5                    27\n              2                     36\n             2.5                    45\n              3                     54\n\nmax dose\n   ‚óè‚Äã to give 1 carpule, the patient must weigh at least 18 pounds\n   ‚óè‚Äã to give 1.5 carpules, the patient must weigh at least 27 pounds\n   ‚óè‚Äã to give 2 carpules, the patient must weight at least 36 pounds\n   ‚óè‚Äã to give 2.5 carpules, the patient must weight at least 45 pounds\n   ‚óè‚Äã to give 3 carpules, the patient must weigh at least 54 pounds\n\nnitrous oxide contraindications\n     ‚óè‚Äã inner ear infections\n     ‚óè‚Äã blocked nasal passages\n     ‚óè‚Äã COPD\n     ‚óè‚Äã pre-existing nausea or vomiting\n     ‚óè‚Äã claustrophobia or emotional disturbances\n     ‚óè‚Äã bleomycin sulfate (chemo drug)\n     ‚óè‚Äã methylenetetrahydrofolate reductase deficiency\n     ‚óè‚Äã cobalamin deficiency\n     ‚óè‚Äã nitrous oxide used in past 7 days"
