"body": "peds composite ‚Äî class II: steps\n    1.‚Äã check in ‚Äî present patient to instructor\n              ‚óã‚Äã you present the patient to your instructor before you call them in / sit them in the chair (!)\n              ‚óã‚Äã present your patient: patient age, gender, medical history, significant dental history, patient behavior\n              ‚óã‚Äã present your restorative plan: procedure(s) for today, sequence (multiple teeth), etc.\n              ‚óã‚Äã present your anesthesia plan: what anesthetic, type of injection (where), how much anesthetic, nitrous oxide\n              ‚óã‚Äã present your isolation plan\n              ‚óã‚Äã other things to mention: how recent is treatment plan, date of last radiographs\n    2.‚Äã call your patient in\n              ‚óã‚Äã go find your pt & guardian in the waiting room\n              ‚óã‚Äã ask the guardian if anything has changed (med history, medications, allergies, etc.)\n              ‚óã‚Äã explain to the guardian what you‚Äôre going to do today & how long they can expect to wait\n              ‚óã‚Äã warn the guardian that if the cavity is deep or bigger than expected, a SSC and/or pulpotomy may be required\n              ‚óã‚Äã leave guardian in waiting room & bring patient back\n              ‚óã‚Äã weigh the pt\n    3.‚Äã administer nitrous oxide, if planned\n    4.‚Äã give local anesthetic\n              ‚óã‚Äã 1 carpule is the limit ‚Äî check with instructor before delivering more than 1 carpule\n              ‚óã‚Äã use the short (blue) needle, even for IANs (unless pt is an older/bigger teenager)\n    5.‚Äã select a shade\n    6.‚Äã isolate\n              ‚óã‚Äã you can use Isodry\n              ‚óã‚Äã if using a rubber dam, don‚Äôt forget to tie floss to the clamp\n              ‚óã‚Äã instead of several holes, punch 2 holes ¬Ω inch apart & use scissors to cut between ‚Äî allows quick placement\n    7.‚Äã pre-wedge\n              ‚óã‚Äã place wooden wedges before prepping to expand PDL; makes restoring a contact easier\n    8.‚Äã complete prep\n              ‚óã‚Äã a slow speed round bur is more conservative (less powerful) than a spoon excavator when removing decay\n              ‚óã‚Äã with a slow speed round bur, infected dentin is drilled out looking wet, cheesy, & clumpy while healthy dentin is\n                  drilled out looking dry, chalky, & dusty ‚Äî this can help you determine if you have removed all decay\n              ‚óã‚Äã if removing an existing composite, you can tell the difference between composite & tooth by thoroughly drying or\n                  scratching with an explorer (composite scratches, tooth does not)\n              ‚óã‚Äã if caries is larger than expected or if you are close to the pulp, check with instructor\n    9.‚Äã check in ‚Äî have instructor check your prep; refine it until they approve\n    10.‚Äã place matrix & wedge\n              ‚óã‚Äã place sectional matrix band (smiling toward occlusal) ‚Üí place plastic wedge ‚Üí place Garrison ring ‚Üí burnish\n                       ‚ñÝ‚Äã don‚Äôt forget to tie floss to the Garrison ring\n\n                       ‚ñÝ‚Äã you can use 2 Garrison rings for an MOD ‚Äî or use one Garrison mesially to restore M contact, switch to\n                            distal to restore D contact, then fill occlusal last\n              ‚óã‚Äã or, place gold matrix band, then burnish\n                       ‚ñÝ‚Äã gold matrix band is used in peds, but honestly it sucks and I‚Äôd just use a Garrison\n    11.‚Äã place liner or base, if indicated\n              ‚óã‚Äã liner:\n                       ‚ñÝ‚Äã indication: when remaining dentin thickness is too thin to prevent bacterial insult to the pulp\n                       ‚ñÝ‚Äã placement: dispense Vitrebond (RMGI) onto mixing pad ‚Üí mix with spatula ‚Üí apply thin layer (0.5 mm)\n                            to pulpal floor ‚Üí light cure 20s\n              ‚óã‚Äã base:\n                       ‚ñÝ‚Äã indication: indirect pulp cap in the area of pulpal proximity, or small mechanical (not carious) exposure\n                       ‚ñÝ‚Äã placement: apply Dycal (calcium hydroxide) only to area of pulpal proximity or mechanical pulpal exposure\n                            ‚Üí cover with Vitrebond (see above)\n    12.‚Äã etch & bond\n              ‚óã‚Äã etch: etch enamel first, then dentin ‚Üí wait 15s ‚Üí rinse 5s ‚Üí lightly dry, leaving dentin moist (use high-evacuation\n                  suction over tooth & lightly quickly air dry; dentin should be glossy without pooling)\n              ‚óã‚Äã bond: apply ScotchBond in a vigorous scrubbing motion for 20s ‚Üí air thin for 5s ‚Üí light cure 10s\n              ‚óã‚Äã if contaminated: re-etch for only 5s, then proceed as usual (rinse, dry, bond, dry, cure)\n    13.‚Äã place composite\n              ‚óã‚Äã place composite in increments & cure 20-40s after each increment (depending on increment size)\n              ‚óã‚Äã cure the final increment for 60s\n    14.‚Äã apply sealant\n              ‚óã‚Äã seal on top of composite\n              ‚óã‚Äã use included sealant brush, microbrush, or explorer to manipulate the sealant material\n              ‚óã‚Äã sealant material is thick ‚Äî make sure you don‚Äôt apply too much or it will interfere with occlusion\n              ‚óã‚Äã light cure 20s (10s on high)\n    15.‚Äã check occlusion & contact\n              ‚óã‚Äã remove rubber dam / isodry\n              ‚óã‚Äã check occlusion with articulating paper\n              ‚óã‚Äã check interproximal contact with floss\n    16.‚Äã finish & polish\n              ‚óã‚Äã composite finishing burs, Shofu, Jiffy Brush\n    17.‚Äã check in ‚Äî have instructor check your restoration\n    18.‚Äã complete codes & note\n              ‚óã‚Äã D2392 (Resin-based comp - 2 surf, post.)\n              ‚óã‚Äã D2393 (Resin-based comp - 3 surf, post.)\n    19.‚Äã check in ‚Äî have instructor swipe your EPR/codes/notes\npeds composite ‚Äî class II: note template\n - y/o female presents to UG Peds with mother for #A-MO composite\n - RMH with mother. No changes.\n - allergies???, no medications, IUTD\n\n Titrated to 40% nitrous oxide / 60% oxygen at 4L/min. Administered for 60 minutes. Applied 20% topical benzocaine & administered 1 carpule of\n 2% lidocaine 1:100k epi with [ 30G 25mm / 27G 35 mm ] needle as IAN & long buccal block on right / buccal infiltration #A.\n\n #A-MO\n Placed Isodry (size P). Removed existing failing MOD amalgam restoration. Excavated decay using high & slow speed burs. Prepared cavity\n preparation to ideal form. Placed Garrison system with matrix band & wedge, burnished. / Gold matrix band placed. Etched with 35% phosphoric\n acid for 15s, rinsed 5s, gently dried leaving dentin moist. Applied Scotchbond Universal 20s, air dried 5s, cured 10s. Applied shade A2 Renamel\n nanofill composite in increments, each cured 20s, with 40s final cure. Finished restoration with finishing diamond burs, polished with Shofu & Jiffy\n brush. Evaluated interproximal contact with floss, adjusted to ideal. Evaluated occlusion with articulating paper, adjusted to ideal.\n\n Patient given 100% oxygen at 4L/min for 5 minutes. Patient released in good condition. Informed mother that pt is still numb, monitor lip & soft\n tissue biting.\n\n - behavior: F4 --\n - NV:\n - Sarah Swade / Dr."
